               <!--<desc type="site-data">
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000288-1">Yongle Palace(永樂宮) is one of the "ancestral temples" of the Quanzhen School of Taoism(全真教), dedicated to the semi-legendary immortal Lü Dongbin(呂洞賓). The original site of the palace was located in Yongle Town(永樂鎮), about 22 kilometers west of Ruicheng County(芮城縣), Shanxi Province（Du 1963, 3-5）. During the late 1950s and early 1960s, under the lead of the ancient building renovation office(古代建築修整所) and the Shanxi Provincial Cultural Management Committee(山西省文管會), the entire temple complex was moved to its present location in Longquan Village(龍泉村), 3 kilometers north of Ruicheng County, to make way for a dam construction project（Katz 1999, 1-4).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000288-2">According to legend, the site was originally the residence of Lü Dongbin, then converted to "Lügong Ci(呂公祠)" until <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang Dynasty</term> and changed to a guan(观) in the late <term ref="/keyword/k000036">Jin Dynasty</term>. In the fourth year of Chunyou(淳祐) in the <term ref="/keyword/k000076">Southern Song Dynasty</term> (1244), the temple was destroyed by war, and it was reconstructed until the third year of <term ref="/keyword/k0000101">Yuan</term> Zhongtong(元中統)（1262）, renamed "Da Chunyang Wanshou Gong(大純陽萬壽宮)". Based on the inscriptions, some construction activities in various extents undertook in both the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming Dynasty</term> and the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing Dynasty</term>（Su 1962, 80-87）. At the beginning of the 20th century, Yongle Palace has been in a state of no one to manage. It was not until the scholars rediscovered the site in 1951 and the Chinese Communist government established the "Yongle Palace Cultural Relics Depository(永樂宮文物保管所)" that the Yongle Palace began to gain widespread attention and proper protection（Du 1963, 3-5).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000288-3">The current distribution of Yongle Palace is divided into two layers of palace walls inside and outside（Katz 1999, 43-47）. Without east-west side halls and surrounding verandah house ,the main relics are arranged on the main axis of the north-south direction. From south to north are the Gate(大門),the Longhu Hall(龍虎殿, or Wuji Gate 無極門), the Sanqing Hall(三清殿, or Wuji Hall 無極殿), the Chunyang Hall(純陽殿, Huncheng Hall 混成殿), and Chongyang Hall(重陽殿, or Qizhen Hall 七真殿). The Qiuzu Hall(丘祖殿) at the end of the axis and the halls on both sides of the Chunyang Hall have been destroyed, and only the ruins remain. There are other historical relics such as Lüzu Ci(呂祖祠) on the west side outside the inner palace wall（Du 1963, 3-5).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="en">For the study of Yongle Palace, its murals in the Yuan Dynasty have always been the focus of academia. Among them, the Chaoyuan Tu(朝元圖) in the Sanqing Hall and the " Chunyang Dijun Shenyou Xianhua Zhi Tu(純陽帝君神遊顯化之圖) " in the Chunyang Hall are the most well-preserved. With the high artistic and research value, the murals have been interpreted and widely discussed by many scholars.</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#bibl000288-1">永樂宮建築群是道教全真教派的祖庭之一，原址位於山西省芮城縣西部22公里的永樂鎮(原為永樂縣)（Du 1963, 3-5）。後因其位於治理黃河的水利工程的淹沒區內,1959年古代建築修整所與山西省文管會以及地、縣有關部門組織當地社員和工人將永樂宮整體搬遷至芮城縣城北3公里的龍泉村東側（Katz 1999, 1-4）。</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#bibl000288-2">永樂宮最初相傳為呂洞賓故居,唐代改其宅為”呂公祠”,金朝末年易祠為觀。南宋淳祐四年(1244年)道觀毀於戰火,元中統三年重建後改號為“大純陽萬壽宮”。據碑刻和殿壁題記,明代和清代都經歷過不同程度的建築活動（Su 1962, 80-87）。20世紀初,永樂宮一直處於無人管理的狀態。直至1951年學界重新發現永樂宮,中國共產黨政府成立”永樂宮文物保管所”之後,永樂宮才開始受到廣泛的關注和妥善的保護（Du 1963, 3-5）。</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#bibl000288-3">永樂宮現狀分為內外兩層宮牆,在南北向的主要軸線上排列有主要的文物建築,不設東西配殿和周圍廊屋（Katz 1999, 43-47）。從南至北分別是大門(宮門)、龍虎殿(無極門)、三清殿(無極殿)、純陽殿(混成殿)和重陽殿(七真殿)。最後的丘祖殿和純陽殿兩側的”朵殿”已毀,今只存遺址。內宮牆之外西側尚有呂祖祠等歷史遺存（Du 1963, 3-5）。</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">對於永樂宮的研究而言,它的元代壁畫一直是學界重點關注的對象。其中,三清殿內的”朝元圖”和純陽殿內的 “純陽帝君神遊顯化之圖”保存最為完好,藝術和研究價值很高,受到諸多學者的解讀和討論。</p>
               </desc>
               -->
